        V12.6 Like/Dislike Button rework:
            Goals:
                ✔ Ability to vote on article WITHOUT the need to login. @done(18:04 - 21/05/21)
                ✔ Limit to 1 vote per cache @done(18:04 - 21/05/21)
            To-Do:
                ✔ Look at current code and see what can be reused. @done(18:04 - 17/05/21)
                    ✔ I had a look but I think I can do better with what I've learned since I first built the component. Especially now that I don't require being logged in. So im going to build a new component and see what happens. @done(18:04 - 21/05/21)
                ✔ I have a solution in place that lets you vote on articles and have that vote saved throughout the website. It took a while, and multiple iterations of the code, to get the UI just as I want it but I managed it in the end. Of course the main flaw is still the vulnerability to vote manipulation but I don't know to avoid that without requiring a login. @done(18:16 - 21/05/21)

                ✔ I suppose one method would be to update the database and undo the likes/dislikes when clearing the cache but that just seems convoluted and I don't want to go down that route. This project is already running way too long as it is. @done(18:16 - 21/05/21)

                ✔ The Like/Dislike buttons are in place so let's move on. @done(18:16 - 21/05/21)


            Issues:
                 Vulnerable to manipulation, you could clear the cache -> vote and then repeat to upvote an article forever. However, I don't care about that for this project so I choose to ignore it. This is really about me understanding the interaction between React/JavaScript and updating a firebase database.
                 I've come to accept that I don't know how to create a like button without the use of local storage. My inspiration for this is the BBC live text page but they're probably using some server side tech that detects a user and works around not having local storage or an account. Otherwise i don't know how to do it
                ...or I'm just missing something very obvious.
                there has to be vote manipulation protection of some sort that skips the front end entirely.
                 Maybe something blocks a client from multiple interactions etc in the server side.
             If that's the case then I think I need to stop worrying about this. I have a solution that works for my purposes(react development and learning) so its probably not a good idea to try and compete or compare myself with the BBC.




