// Random Notes - Make sure the below follow a similiar numbering structure
    ->Tags.js
    -->newState.slice(0,30)

    ->news-item-loop.js
    -->newState.slice(0,30)
    -->arrayStartState:30
    -->arrayEndState:35

    ->scrollCheck.js
    -->arrayStartState:30
    -->arrayEndState:35





1: {key: "7", id: 546, hidden: undefined, author: "Callie Medina", title: "lacus. Cras interdum. Nunc sollicitudin commodo ipsum. Suspendisse", …}
2: {key: "8", id: 536, hidden: undefined, author: "Ivory Alford", title: "lectus convallis est, vitae sodales nisi magna sed", …}
3: {key: "9", id: 241, hidden: undefined, author: "Paloma Ward", title: "Nam ac nulla. In tincidunt", …}
4: {key: "10", id: 605, hidden: undefined, author: "Jesse Blackburn", title: "dignissim pharetra. Nam ac nulla. In tincidunt", …}

This is the latest release note entry. In the future, I will leave the talking to the blog, but I wanted to leave something here to mark the point I finally caught up. Version 11 has been a milestone in my commitment to, and understanding of, React.js and I am proud of where theKnews is at the moment. 

I've been hard at work for over 2 months trying to get this release right, thinking I was close only to notice that I needed to rip out a quarter of the code and redo it, as you can see in Version 11 where I did that 3 times. I would go as far as to say, that, unlike triggers broom, V11 is a completley different website from V10, fundamental aesthetics aside.

It's a project literally years in the making and I'm looking forward to where it goes next.

My version numbers are...a choice. I am aware of that but they make sense to me so it's never really bothered me that much. Just know that the 11.1 to 11.5 was me trying to fix an issue with React Router and the .4 was tweaking the infinite scroll detection rate. In hindsight I should have probably gone for something like 11.0.1, 11.0.1.1, 11.0.1.2 etc but I didn't so 11.5.4 is what I ended up with for a release that is a few small bug fixes and not a piece of software getting a mid life update.